00:00:20.970 --> 00:00:23.220 align:middle line:90%
Do you remember your dreams?

00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:25.110 align:middle line:10%
Have you ever
experienced a dream that

00:00:25.110 --> 00:00:27.930 align:middle line:10%
felt like it really happened?

00:00:27.930 --> 00:00:30.750 align:middle line:10%
Or have you ever become
lucid during a dream,

00:00:30.750 --> 00:00:33.630 align:middle line:10%
aware of the fact that
you were dreaming?

00:00:33.630 --> 00:00:38.010 align:middle line:84%
We spend nearly one third
of our life sleeping.

00:00:38.010 --> 00:00:40.530 align:middle line:84%
What's happening
during this time?

00:00:40.530 --> 00:00:42.180 align:middle line:90%
Of course, our body is resting.

00:00:42.180 --> 00:00:45.480 align:middle line:84%
But what's happening with our
spirits, our consciousness,

00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:46.950 align:middle line:90%
and mind?

00:00:46.950 --> 00:00:51.570 align:middle line:84%
Could it be that dreams are
another version of reality.

00:00:51.570 --> 00:00:55.560 align:middle line:84%
Ever since I was really young,
I've had super vivid dreams.

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:57.690 align:middle line:84%
Being aware of my
dreams and sharing them

00:00:57.690 --> 00:01:01.200 align:middle line:84%
with my parents and friends has
always been a part of my life.

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:04.650 align:middle line:84%
Because of this, my dream time
has been a very enriching part

00:01:04.650 --> 00:01:06.390 align:middle line:90%
of my life.

00:01:06.390 --> 00:01:08.700 align:middle line:10%
Both my parents
were active students

00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:10.980 align:middle line:10%
of the Edgar Cayce readings.

00:01:10.980 --> 00:01:14.220 align:middle line:10%
And in addition, my dad studied
parapsychology and the work

00:01:14.220 --> 00:01:16.230 align:middle line:10%
of Carl Jung while in college.

00:01:16.230 --> 00:01:19.740 align:middle line:84%
And my mom's a college professor
of inter and intrapersonal

00:01:19.740 --> 00:01:21.360 align:middle line:90%
communications.

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:23.820 align:middle line:84%
Plus, she was really involved
with the Monroe Institute

00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:27.330 align:middle line:84%
that explores consciousness
and journeys out of body.

00:01:27.330 --> 00:01:29.340 align:middle line:84%
So we developed a
family tradition

00:01:29.340 --> 00:01:32.280 align:middle line:84%
of sharing dreams and
interpreting them, especially

00:01:32.280 --> 00:01:34.920 align:middle line:90%
when they felt significant.

00:01:34.920 --> 00:01:37.140 align:middle line:84%
In this episode, I'd
like to share with you

00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:41.230 align:middle line:84%
some of what I've learned about
our life in the dream time.

00:01:41.230 --> 00:01:45.270 align:middle line:84%
Dreams can be such a
useful guide in our life.

00:01:45.270 --> 00:01:48.780 align:middle line:84%
They can help us solve problems,
receive insights, and higher

00:01:48.780 --> 00:01:50.970 align:middle line:90%
teachings from higher planes.

00:01:50.970 --> 00:01:54.130 align:middle line:84%
Learn about ourselves
and so much more.

00:01:54.130 --> 00:01:56.370 align:middle line:84%
So I'd like to share some
useful methods with you

00:01:56.370 --> 00:01:59.890 align:middle line:84%
for becoming more in tune
with your dream time.

00:01:59.890 --> 00:02:02.820 align:middle line:84%
When we talk about
dreams, the first question

00:02:02.820 --> 00:02:06.780 align:middle line:84%
that often comes up is,
does everybody dream?

00:02:06.780 --> 00:02:09.840 align:middle line:84%
Some people swear
that they don't dream.

00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:14.410 align:middle line:84%
But science shows dreaming
is a part of our sleep cycle.

00:02:14.410 --> 00:02:18.300 align:middle line:84%
Even if we aren't aware of
it or remember our dreams

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:21.660 align:middle line:90%
when we wake up, we all dream.

00:02:21.660 --> 00:02:24.510 align:middle line:84%
Everyone goes through
a couple of REM cycles

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:27.510 align:middle line:84%
at night, which is marked
by rapid eye movement

00:02:27.510 --> 00:02:28.870 align:middle line:90%
during our sleep.

00:02:28.870 --> 00:02:30.840 align:middle line:84%
And during this
time, the brain is

00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:34.590 align:middle line:84%
firing off with similar
patterns to when we're conscious

00:02:34.590 --> 00:02:35.820 align:middle line:90%
and awake.

00:02:35.820 --> 00:02:38.580 align:middle line:84%
Only in this case,
we're dreaming.

00:02:38.580 --> 00:02:41.040 align:middle line:84%
But for the most
part, our brain can't

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:45.990 align:middle line:84%
tell the difference between
dreaming and wakefulness.

00:02:45.990 --> 00:02:48.220 align:middle line:90%
So everybody dreams.

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:52.770 align:middle line:84%
Whether we remember it or not
is another matter altogether.

00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:55.980 align:middle line:84%
So what's happening
when we dream?

00:02:55.980 --> 00:02:59.370 align:middle line:84%
Are dreams meaningless
or meaningful?

00:02:59.370 --> 00:03:01.290 align:middle line:84%
And how can we
engage our dream time

00:03:01.290 --> 00:03:05.230 align:middle line:84%
to support our
overall progression?

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:06.940 align:middle line:90%
There are many types of dreams.

00:03:06.940 --> 00:03:08.020 align:middle line:10%
